         <abstract>
            <p>Notebook computers, such as the TRS-80 Model 100 and the NEC 8201, provide both the students and the teacher with the unique opportunity of bringing into the classroom a truly portable, self-contained computer with integrated, non-volatile memory. Two programs that are useful to the language student and that take full advantage of the unique features of these computers are the Course A uthoring Program, which allows the teacher to create computerized tutorial lessons without recourse to programming languages, and FLASH, a computerized flash card manipulator. Both programs utilize text files that are created by the computer's built-in editor and can, with minimal effort, be converted for implementation on any computer system for which a text editor and appropriate memory storage facility are available.</p>
